<Title>Exploring the Interior in Topology</Title>

<Paragraph>The concept of **interior** is fundamental in topology, providing insight into the "inside" of sets within topological spaces.</Paragraph>

<SubHead>Definition</SubHead>

<Paragraph>Given a subset $A$ of a topological space $X$, the **interior** of $A$ (denoted $A^\circ$ or $\textInt(A)$) is:
- The union of all open sets contained in $A$
- The largest open subset of $X$ contained in $A$
</Paragraph>
<SubHead> Key Properties</SubHead>

1. **Always Open**: $A^\circ$ is always an open set
2. **Nested Relation**: If $A \subseteq B$ then $A^\circ \subseteq B^\circ$
3. **Idempotent**: $(A^\circ)^\circ = A^\circ$
4. **Intersection Preservation**: $(A \cap B)^\circ = A^\circ \cap B^\circ$
